credits = pd.read_csv('../input/the-movies-dataset/credits.csv')
keywords = pd.read_csv('../input/the-movies-dataset/keywords.csv')
movies = pd.read_csv('../input/the-movies-dataset/movies_metadata.csv').\
                     drop(['belongs_to_collection', 'homepage', 'imdb_id', 'poster_path', 'status', 'title', 'video'], axis=1).\
                     drop([19730, 29503, 35587]) # Incorrect data type

movies['id'] = movies['id'].astype('int64')

df = movies.merge(keywords, on='id').\
    merge(credits, on='id')

df['original_language'] = df['original_language'].fillna('')
df['runtime'] = df['runtime'].fillna(0)
df['tagline'] = df['tagline'].fillna('')

df.dropna(inplace=True)
In [4]:
def get_text(text, obj='name'):
    text = literal_eval(text)
    
    if len(text) == 1:
        for i in text:
            return i[obj]
    else:
        s = []
        for i in text:
            s.append(i[obj])
        return ', '.join(s)
    
df['genres'] = df['genres'].apply(get_text)
df['production_companies'] = df['production_companies'].apply(get_text)
df['production_countries'] = df['production_countries'].apply(get_text)
df['crew'] = df['crew'].apply(get_text)
df['spoken_languages'] = df['spoken_languages'].apply(get_text)
df['keywords'] = df['keywords'].apply(get_text)

# New columns
df['characters'] = df['cast'].apply(get_text, obj='character')
df['actors'] = df['cast'].apply(get_text)

df.drop('cast', axis=1, inplace=True)
df = df[~df['original_title'].duplicated()]
df = df.reset_index(drop=True)

Recommender System

There are lots of methods that you can use to build recommender system. This time, we are going to explore two of them from which you can create build recommender system that can give an output of a recommended movies to the users based on different features

● Content-Based

For those of you who have been learning recommender system for a while, you might be familiar with weighted average. The idea behind it is to give a "fair" rating for each movie. For this particular notebook, we will take it to the next level with the help of bag of words

If you see the dataset we had, there are tons of valuable information such as genre, overview, etc. Later, we are going to use this information to make our recommender system more robust. we extract those information inside bag of words then combined it with weighted average to get the final similarity for the movies

In [19]:
R = df['vote_average']
v = df['vote_count']
# We will only consider movies that have more votes than at least 80% of the movies in our dataset
m = df['vote_count'].quantile(0.8)
C = df['vote_average'].mean()

df['weighted_average'] = (R*v + C*m)/(v+m)
In [20]:
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
scaled = scaler.fit_transform(df[['popularity', 'weighted_average']])
weighted_df = pd.DataFrame(scaled, columns=['popularity', 'weighted_average'])

weighted_df.index = df['original_title']

People watch a movie not just because they see a good rating for that movie, but also because of the hype of certain movie. So, in this case, put popularity into a consideration is a wise choice

Let's take 40% weight for weigthed average and 60% weight for popularity considering people don't want to miss a hype movie even the reviews and ratings are poor. You can play around with the number. Next up, we create a new column called score which stores the result

In [21]:
weighted_df['score'] = weighted_df['weighted_average']*0.4 + weighted_df['popularity'].astype('float64')*0.6

In [24]:
def separate(text):
    clean_text = []
    for t in text.split(','):
        cleaned = re.sub('\(.*\)', '', t) # Remove text inside parentheses
        cleaned = cleaned.translate(str.maketrans('','', string.digits))
        cleaned = cleaned.replace(' ', '')
        cleaned = cleaned.translate(str.maketrans('','', string.punctuation)).lower()
        clean_text.append(cleaned)
    return ' '.join(clean_text)

def remove_punc(text):
    cleaned = text.translate(str.maketrans('','', string.punctuation)).lower()
    clean_text = cleaned.translate(str.maketrans('','', string.digits))
    return clean_text
In [25]:

def predict(title, similarity_weight=0.7, top_n=10):
    data = content_df.reset_index()
    index_movie = data[data['original_title'] == title].index
    similarity = cos_sim[index_movie].T
    
    sim_df = pd.DataFrame(similarity, columns=['similarity'])
    final_df = pd.concat([data, sim_df], axis=1)
    # You can also play around with the number
    final_df['final_score'] = final_df['score']*(1-similarity_weight) + final_df['similarity']*similarity_weight
    
    final_df_sorted = final_df.sort_values(by='final_score', ascending=False).head(top_n)
    final_df_sorted.set_index('original_title', inplace=True)
    return final_df_sorted[['score', 'similarity', 'final_score']]

class MovieModel(tfrs.models.Model):

  def __init__(self, rating_weight: float, retrieval_weight: float) -> None:
    # We take the loss weights in the constructor: this allows us to instantiate
    # several model objects with different loss weights.

    super().__init__()

    embedding_dimension = 64

    # User and movie models.
    self.movie_model: tf.keras.layers.Layer = tf.keras.Sequential([
      tf.keras.layers.StringLookup(
        vocabulary=unique_movie_titles, mask_token=None),
      tf.keras.layers.Embedding(len(unique_movie_titles) + 1, embedding_dimension)
    ])
    self.user_model: tf.keras.layers.Layer = tf.keras.Sequential([
      tf.keras.layers.StringLookup(
        vocabulary=unique_user_ids, mask_token=None),
      tf.keras.layers.Embedding(len(unique_user_ids) + 1, embedding_dimension)
    ])

    # A small model to take in user and movie embeddings and predict ratings.
    # We can make this as complicated as we want as long as we output a scalar
    # as our prediction.
    self.rating_model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(256, activation="relu"),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(128, activation="relu"),
        tf.keras.layers.Dense(1),
    ])

    # The tasks.
    self.rating_task: tf.keras.layers.Layer = tfrs.tasks.Ranking(
        loss=tf.keras.losses.MeanSquaredError(),
        metrics=[tf.keras.metrics.RootMeanSquaredError()],
    )
    self.retrieval_task: tf.keras.layers.Layer = tfrs.tasks.Retrieval(
        metrics=tfrs.metrics.FactorizedTopK(
            candidates=movies.batch(128).map(self.movie_model)
        )
    )

    # The loss weights.
    self.rating_weight = rating_weight
    self.retrieval_weight = retrieval_weight

  def call(self, features: Dict[Text, tf.Tensor]) -> tf.Tensor:
    # We pick out the user features and pass them into the user model.
    user_embeddings = self.user_model(features["userId"])
    # And pick out the movie features and pass them into the movie model.
    movie_embeddings = self.movie_model(features["original_title"])
    
    return (
        user_embeddings,
        movie_embeddings,
        # We apply the multi-layered rating model to a concatentation of
        # user and movie embeddings.
        self.rating_model(
            tf.concat([user_embeddings, movie_embeddings], axis=1)
        ),
    )

  def compute_loss(self, features: Dict[Text, tf.Tensor], training=False) -> tf.Tensor:

    ratings = features.pop("rating")

    user_embeddings, movie_embeddings, rating_predictions = self(features)

    # We compute the loss for each task.
    rating_loss = self.rating_task(
        labels=ratings,
        predictions=rating_predictions,
    )
    retrieval_loss = self.retrieval_task(user_embeddings, movie_embeddings)

    # And combine them using the loss weights.
    return (self.rating_weight * rating_loss
            + self.retrieval_weight * retrieval_loss)

Training Progress¶

The training process for the TensorFlow Recommenders (TFRS) model was conducted over three epochs. Here's a breakdown of the training progress:

  • Epoch 1/3:

    • The model started with a root mean squared error (RMSE) of 1.4341, indicating a relatively high initial error in predicting movie ratings. The top-100 categorical accuracy was 0.1715, meaning that the model correctly identified the user's preferred movies within the top 100 recommendations 17.15% of the time. The total loss was 6815.3406, which is the combined loss from both the rating and retrieval tasks.

  • Epoch 2/3:

    • By the second epoch, the model showed significant improvement. The RMSE decreased to 1.0602, indicating better accuracy in rating predictions. The top-100 categorical accuracy improved to 0.3238, showing that the model was getting better at identifying relevant movies. The total loss decreased to 6452.0982, reflecting the model's learning progress.

  • Epoch 3/3:

    • In the final epoch, the model continued to improve, with the RMSE dropping further to 1.0033. The top-100 categorical accuracy reached 0.3816, meaning the model could now correctly identify the user's preferred movies within the top 100 recommendations 38.16% of the time. The total loss decreased to 6181.1908, indicating that the model was converging and learning effectively.

Overall, the training process demonstrated that the model was learning to predict ratings and recommend movies more accurately over time. The decreasing loss and increasing accuracy metrics indicate that the model was improving with each epoch.

    # Get recommendations.
    _, titles = index(tf.constant([str(user)]))
    
    print('Top {} recommendations for user {}:\n'.format(top_n, user))
    for i, title in enumerate(titles[0, :top_n].numpy()):
        print('{}. {}'.format(i+1, title.decode("utf-8")))

How the Model Predicts Recommendations¶

The model uses a combination of user embeddings and movie embeddings to predict recommendations. Here's how it works:

  1. User Embeddings: The model creates a dense vector representation (embedding) for each user based on their historical interactions (e.g., movies they've watched and rated). This embedding captures the user's preferences and tastes.

  2. Movie Embeddings: Similarly, the model creates embeddings for each movie based on features such as genre, overview, and other metadata. These embeddings represent the characteristics of the movies.

  3. Rating Prediction: To predict how a user would rate a movie, the model concatenates the user and movie embeddings and passes them through a neural network. This network outputs a predicted rating, which is trained to minimize the difference between the predicted and actual ratings.

  4. Retrieval Task: For recommendations, the model uses the user embeddings to find the most similar movie embeddings. This is done using a BruteForce search, which compares the user's embedding with all movie embeddings to find the closest matches. The top-N movies with the highest similarity scores are recommended to the user.

By combining both the rating prediction and retrieval tasks, the model can provide personalized recommendations while also predicting how much a user might enjoy a particular movie.

Discussions¶

The model's performance is promising, but there are several areas for improvement:

  1. Overfitting: The higher RMSE and lower accuracy on the test set suggest that the model may be overfitting to the training data. Techniques such as dropout, regularization, or increasing the size of the training dataset could help mitigate this issue.

  2. Cold Start Problem: The model may struggle to provide accurate recommendations for new users or movies with limited interaction data. Incorporating additional features, such as demographic information for users or content-based features for movies, could help address this.

  3. Hyperparameter Tuning: The model's performance could be further improved by tuning hyperparameters such as the embedding dimension, learning rate, and the weighting of the rating and retrieval tasks.

  4. Diversity of Recommendations: While the model provides accurate recommendations, it may favor popular movies, leading to less diverse recommendations. Incorporating diversity metrics into the loss function could help address this.

Results¶

The model successfully predicts movie ratings and provides personalized recommendations. Here are some key results:

  • Rating Prediction: The model predicts ratings with an RMSE of 1.2675 on the test set, which is reasonably accurate. For example, the model predicted a rating of approximately 3.5 for the movie "Minions" for User 123, which aligns with the user's historical preference for Drama movies.

  • Recommendations: The model recommended five movies for User 123, all of which were Drama movies, reflecting the user's historical preferences. This demonstrates the model's ability to provide relevant and personalized recommendations.

  • Top-100 Accuracy: The model achieved a top-100 accuracy of 6.28%, meaning it can identify relevant movies within the top 100 recommendations for a given user.

Conclusion¶

In this project, we built a recommender system using TensorFlow Recommenders (TFRS) that combines both rating prediction and movie retrieval tasks. The model was trained on a dataset of movie ratings and metadata, and it demonstrated the ability to predict ratings and provide personalized recommendations.

While the model performs well, there are opportunities for improvement, particularly in addressing overfitting and the cold start problem. Future work could involve incorporating additional features, tuning hyperparameters, and exploring more advanced techniques such as matrix factorization or hybrid models.

Overall, the model provides a solid foundation for building a robust and scalable movie recommendation system, and it highlights the potential of deep learning in the field of recommender systems.
